tributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCountless books and articles have traced the impact of colonialism and public policy on Canada's First Nations, but few have explored the impact of Aboriginal thought on public discourse and policy development in Canada. First Nations, First Thoughts brings together Aboriginal and non-Aboriginal scholars who cut through the prevailing orthodoxy to reveal Indigenous thinkers and activists as a pervasive presence in diverse political, constitutional, and cultural debates and arenas, including urban spaces, historical texts, public policy, and cultural heritage preservation. This innovative, thought-provoking collection contributes to the decolonization process by encouraging us to imagine a stronger, fairer Canada in which Aboriginal self-government and expression can be fully realized.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh1 aBolton, Stephanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Alison K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrownlie, Robin Jarvis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKovach, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLadner, Kiera L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacDonald, Fiona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCartney, Leslie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurphy, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPatterson, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeers, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://